Harvard Students Are Taking Courses to Get Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year aims to teach all graduates more sleep in order to combat the growing macho culture of learning by staying awake all night with the help of caffeine.
One researcher found that students at the world’s leading university often know nothing when it comes to basic self-care.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, is designing the course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a speech on the impact of insufficient sleep on learning.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in the last year?’
She said that no one, ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told the Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help in academic and athletic performance, and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after they discovered that students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there’s a picture of a student’s home where students press on coffee cups, curtains, shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how insufficient sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of the students right away.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know about the effects on health when you choose to smoke a cigarette,” added Professor Chaisler.
The culture of pride in "working all night" still exists, he said, and in addition, modern technology and increasing pressure on students mean that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
To have enough sleep, with good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid obesity, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go hungry.
Raymond Sow, a 19-year-old California student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year, in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to act for a course across the student city.
He hopes that the next step is to require all graduates to complete a similar program before joining the competitive institution.
