Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of income for the economy of the Central Sulawesi Province, especially the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also an important activity in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morovali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Indonesia's disaster mitigation agency says Palu and Dongala have been hit by the tsunami several times in the past 100 years.
In 1938, the tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Dongala.
The tsunami also struck western Dongala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years are:
2004: A large earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26 caused a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them were drowned.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, on the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that destroyed the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 struck an area near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 struck one of the Mentawai Islands, near Sumatra, causing a tsunami that reached up to 10 meters and destroyed dozens of villages, killing about 300 people.
2016: An earthquake with a shallow focus hit the Pidi Jaya district of Aceh, causing devastation and panic as it reminded people of the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
This time the earthquake did not cause a tsunami, but more than 100 people were killed by the collapsed buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
