U.S. Attorneys Seek Rare Death Penalty for Suspected Terrorist Attack in New York City
NEW YORK (AP) - Federal prosecutors are seeking the death penalty for Saifulo Saipov, the suspect in the New York terror attack in which eight people were killed, a rare sentence that has not been carried out in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
Saipov, 30, allegedly used a rental truck at the Home Depot in October to carry out an attack on a bike path on the West Side Highway in Lower Manhattan and to overtake pedestrians and cyclists who found themselves in his path.
In order to justify the death penalty, prosecutors will need to prove that Saipov "intentionally" killed the eight victims and "intentionally" inflicted serious bodily harm, according to a report of intent to seek the death penalty filed in the Southern District of New York.
According to court documents, it is possible to pronounce the death penalty on both of these grounds of the indictment.
A few weeks after the attack, the Federal Grand Jury launched an indictment against Saipov on 22 grounds, including eight counts of murder for the purposes of racketeering, which is usually used by federal prosecutors in cases of organized crime, as well as charges of violence and mob destruction.
The attack required "detailed planning and intent," the prosecutors said, describing Saipov's way of carrying out the attack as "gross, cruel and perverse."
"Saifulo Habibulaevic Saipov caused, injuries, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicolas Cleves, En-Laure Decat, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlej, Hernan Mehmet, Hernan Mehmet and Hernan Diena"
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It’s been a decade since a death penalty case was prosecuted in the Southern District of New York.
The defendant, Calid Barnes, was convicted of murdering two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty was carried out in a federal case in New York was in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple who were executed after being convicted of conspiring to spy on the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years ago.
Both were sentenced to death by electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, born in Uzbekistan, showed no regrets in the days and months following the attack, according to court documents.
Police said he told investigators that he felt good about what he had done.
According to the indictment, Saipov told authorities that he was inspired to carry out the attack after watching ISIS videos on his phone.
Police also said he had asked to place the ISIS flag in his hospital room.
He said he was innocent on all 22 counts of the charge.
David Paton, one of the federal public defenders representing Saipov, said they were "obviously disappointed" by the prosecutor's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty, instead of accepting a guilty plea and issuing a life sentence without the possibility of acquittal, will only prolong the trauma of these events for all involved in them," he said.
Saipov's defense had previously asked prosecutors not to seek the death penalty.
