New information about the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven cutting of algae have been observed in the area of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the ripening of the red algae, stretches about 130 miles off the coast from the northern Pinelas County to the southern Li County.
Parts of the red tide can also be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but the number is still smaller compared to last week.
A red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, the following concentrations have been observed: average concentrations in or on the coast of Pinelas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of the county of Sarasota.
In Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Li and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
There have been no reported cases of respiratory irritation in Northwest Florida over the past week.
